1
00:00:06,333 --> 00:00:07,668
[LAUGHTER]

2
00:00:07,752 --> 00:00:09,419
So, I'm about to go
on the road for a while.

3
00:00:09,503 --> 00:00:12,089
Isn't it weird how, when
you're away from home,

4
00:00:12,173 --> 00:00:13,298
you start missing the little things

5
00:00:13,382 --> 00:00:16,133
you never really thought
about, like your kids?

6
00:00:16,217 --> 00:00:17,927
-[WEAK LAUGHTER]
-Oh.

7
00:00:18,011 --> 00:00:19,095
I thought that would do better.

8
00:00:19,179 --> 00:00:21,722
I guess you all like kids.
To each his own.

9
00:00:21,806 --> 00:00:25,434
Okay, well, I have kids.

10
00:00:25,518 --> 00:00:28,312
And, you know, everybody
seems to get so angry

11
00:00:28,396 --> 00:00:29,689
when you bring one on a plane.

12
00:00:29,773 --> 00:00:31,691
But if the airlines don't want them,

13
00:00:31,775 --> 00:00:34,944
why do they provide those
little child-size bottles of booze?

14
00:00:35,028 --> 00:00:37,238
-[WEAK LAUGHTER]
-Wow.

15
00:00:37,322 --> 00:00:39,573
Not in a laughing mood tonight, huh?

16
00:00:39,657 --> 00:00:41,909
You know, th… there's a Bergman
film playing down the street.

17
00:00:41,993 --> 00:00:43,035
It's about black death.

18
00:00:43,119 --> 00:00:44,620
Maybe you should've gone to that.

19
00:00:44,704 --> 00:00:47,163
Maybe something's missing from my set.

20
00:00:47,247 --> 00:00:49,499
What could it be?

21
00:00:49,583 --> 00:00:52,085
What could it be?

22
00:00:52,169 --> 00:00:53,878
Oh, I know.

23
00:00:53,962 --> 00:00:55,880
A catchphrase.

24
00:00:55,964 --> 00:00:58,049
Yeah, that way I could
do a bunch of crappy jokes,

25
00:00:58,133 --> 00:01:00,552
then save them with one
of my patented zingers.

26
00:01:00,636 --> 00:01:04,139
Something like "Have
yourself a scoop of that!"

27
00:01:04,223 --> 00:01:06,057
-Or "Dock that in your harbor."
-[LAUGHTER]

28
00:01:06,141 --> 00:01:09,520
Or "Stuff that in your pierogi." Yeah.

29
00:01:11,563 --> 00:01:13,982
Guess I'm a little nervous.

30
00:01:14,066 --> 00:01:16,817
I'm opening for Shy Baldwin.

31
00:01:16,901 --> 00:01:20,988
-[ENTHUSIASTIC APPLAUSE]
-Oh, yeah, him you like.

32
00:01:21,072 --> 00:01:23,115
But I won't be on the road by myself.

33
00:01:23,199 --> 00:01:27,286
I'll have a support system.
My manager Susie Myerson.

34
00:01:27,370 --> 00:01:29,329
[LOUD BOOING]

35
00:01:29,413 --> 00:01:31,206
I see you've met.

36
00:01:31,290 --> 00:01:34,376
You know, she's always
believed in me, Susie.

37
00:01:34,460 --> 00:01:36,962
She's pushed me to get better and better.

38
00:01:37,046 --> 00:01:38,714
Sometimes off a cliff, but irregardless,

39
00:01:38,798 --> 00:01:40,632
I'm loyal to her for that.

40
00:01:40,716 --> 00:01:42,843
Because, really, if there's no loyalty,

41
00:01:42,927 --> 00:01:45,137
what's the point of a partnership?

42
00:01:45,221 --> 00:01:47,513
They say if you want loyalty, get a dog.

43
00:01:47,597 --> 00:01:50,433
But even the most loyal
dog will stick its head

44
00:01:50,517 --> 00:01:52,769
in your neighbor's cooze
'cause it wants to get scratched.

45
00:01:52,853 --> 00:01:55,104
I mean, it doesn't mean
the dog doesn't like you,

46
00:01:55,188 --> 00:01:57,899
it just means the dog
isn't that fucking picky.

47
00:02:00,318 --> 00:02:03,112
All right.

48
00:02:03,196 --> 00:02:04,572
Thanks, everybody.

49
00:02:04,656 --> 00:02:06,324
I'm Mrs. Maisel. Good night.

50
00:02:06,408 --> 00:02:07,909
[APPLAUSE]

51
00:02:07,993 --> 00:02:10,244
Good job, Midge. Really good.

52
00:02:10,328 --> 00:02:11,662
I'm sorry, were you even listening?

53
00:02:11,746 --> 00:02:13,623
Oh, no, don't get me
wrong, you were awful.

54
00:02:13,707 --> 00:02:15,416
It was like sitting at my
grandmother's deathbed

55
00:02:15,500 --> 00:02:16,875
all over again, but without snacks.

56
00:02:16,959 --> 00:02:18,293
Thanks for the feedback.

57
00:02:18,377 --> 00:02:19,961
Hey, better to crap
out now then in front of

58
00:02:20,045 --> 00:02:21,171
a thousand people in Vegas.

59
00:02:21,255 --> 00:02:22,506
That would be disastrous.

60
00:02:22,590 --> 00:02:24,299
Really, Jackie, you're
giving me a big head.

61
00:02:24,383 --> 00:02:27,302
Yeah, your head
looked bigger tonight, too.

62
00:02:27,386 --> 00:02:29,137
So what was that,
exactly, all that loyalty stuff?

63
00:02:29,221 --> 00:02:31,681
Just trying to be
inspirational to my audience.

64
00:02:31,765 --> 00:02:34,184
Well, maybe skip
trying to be inspirational

65
00:02:34,268 --> 00:02:35,894
when you open for Shy
and just stick to the funny.

66
00:02:35,978 --> 00:02:37,604
I mean, you're not opening
for the fucking Buddha.

67
00:02:37,688 --> 00:02:39,564
Always a help. Thanks.

68
00:02:39,648 --> 00:02:41,525
-Is that what you really think?
-What?

69
00:02:41,609 --> 00:02:44,236
That I'm sticking my head
in Sophie Lennon's cooze.

70
00:02:44,320 --> 00:02:46,237
I was speaking in general terms.

71
00:02:46,321 --> 00:02:48,531
Okay. Well, try to be specific.

72
00:02:48,615 --> 00:02:49,615
Maybe that'll get you some laughs.

73
00:02:49,699 --> 00:02:53,035
-Okay.
-Okay.

74
00:02:53,119 --> 00:02:55,287
And by the way, "irregardless"?
It's not a word.

75
00:02:55,371 --> 00:02:57,039
-Yes, it is.
-No, it's not.

76
00:02:57,123 --> 00:02:58,541
It's "regardless." That's the word.

77
00:02:58,625 --> 00:03:00,417
Well, I say irregardless.

78
00:03:00,501 --> 00:03:02,044
Just trying to be inspirational.

79
00:03:02,128 --> 00:03:04,380
Well, you've inspired me.

80
00:03:04,464 --> 00:03:06,674
-Go announce the next act.
-I don't want to miss anything.

81
00:03:06,758 --> 00:03:08,884
Go.

82
00:03:08,968 --> 00:03:10,595
Look, I…

83
00:03:12,680 --> 00:03:14,598
JACKIE: Okay, if you
think multiple ocarinas

84
00:03:14,682 --> 00:03:16,474
playing at the same time is depressing,

85
00:03:16,558 --> 00:03:19,185
then you really should have
gone to the fucking Bergman film.

86
00:03:19,269 --> 00:03:20,896
[LAUGHTER]

87
00:03:23,857 --> 00:03:24,858
Miriam Weissman!

88
00:03:24,942 --> 00:03:26,818
God. Mrs. Fulber, you scared me.

89
00:03:26,902 --> 00:03:28,486
What's with all the noise
from your apartment?

90
00:03:28,570 --> 00:03:30,321
There's some sort of party going on.

91
00:03:30,405 --> 00:03:31,656
Let me check. I'm just getting home.

92
00:03:31,740 --> 00:03:33,032
-From where?
-I was out.

93
00:03:33,116 --> 00:03:34,409
-On a school night?
-Yes.

94
00:03:34,493 --> 00:03:36,411
-With boys?
-I got to go, Mrs. Fulber.

95
00:03:36,495 --> 00:03:38,538
-Brush your teeth.
-You're not my babysitter anymore.

96
00:03:38,622 --> 00:03:39,706
ABE: …despite laws.

97
00:03:39,790 --> 00:03:41,249
EZRA: 'Cause the laws
are set by capitalists.

98
00:03:41,333 --> 00:03:42,625
ALAN: The rich have
been using the Constitution

99
00:03:42,709 --> 00:03:44,043
to justify their crimes against the poor.

100
00:03:44,127 --> 00:03:45,503
MADELINE: Marx was the true purist.

101
00:03:45,587 --> 00:03:47,129
Lenin's the little boy
who dumped his bowels

102
00:03:47,213 --> 00:03:48,297
on Karl's genius.

103
00:03:48,381 --> 00:03:50,924
I've never heard it put quite that way,

104
00:03:51,008 --> 00:03:52,676
but I agree with the general sentiment.

105
00:03:52,760 --> 00:03:54,511
Hello… all.

106
00:03:54,595 --> 00:03:56,013
Ah, Miriam.

107
00:03:56,097 --> 00:03:58,557
Let me introduce you to some new friends.

108
00:03:58,641 --> 00:04:01,101
This is Ezra, Alan, and Madeline.

109
00:04:01,185 --> 00:04:02,811
Everybody, this is my daughter Miriam.

110
00:04:02,895 --> 00:04:04,438
-Hello.
-I met my lawyer

111
00:04:04,522 --> 00:04:06,857
at the White Horse Tavern
and fell into a conversation

112
00:04:06,941 --> 00:04:08,358
with these three,
and it was getting late,

113
00:04:08,442 --> 00:04:09,651
and they were closing up.

114
00:04:09,735 --> 00:04:10,652
So I invited them here.

115
00:04:10,736 --> 00:04:13,155
They're starting a weekly paper.

116
00:04:13,239 --> 00:04:14,406
More of a revolutionary broadsheet.

117
00:04:14,490 --> 00:04:15,991
And we think Abe should be a part of it.

118
00:04:16,075 --> 00:04:19,243
Sounds great.
It's nice you're making friends.

119
00:04:19,327 --> 00:04:21,245
We were all just
debating what to call it.

120
00:04:21,329 --> 00:04:24,498
And the final choices are <i>The New Jive</i>

121
00:04:24,582 --> 00:04:27,418
and <i>It's the Sixties, Man!</i>
Two timeless names.

122
00:04:27,502 --> 00:04:29,086
MADELINE: Alan came
up with both of those.

123
00:04:29,170 --> 00:04:31,548
He's so expressive.

124
00:04:35,051 --> 00:04:38,888
This was a little distracting
at first, but you get used to it.

125
00:04:38,972 --> 00:04:40,807
And the comrades in the study?

126
00:04:42,726 --> 00:04:45,228
I did not know they were there.

127
00:04:45,312 --> 00:04:46,229
Yeah, that's Corey and Bishop.

128
00:04:46,313 --> 00:04:47,312
We invited them to come and bunk here.

129
00:04:47,396 --> 00:04:50,232
Okay, gang, so… carry on.

130
00:04:50,316 --> 00:04:53,109
But if you could
carry on a little quieter.

131
00:04:53,193 --> 00:04:55,028
Ideas are thunderclaps.

132
00:04:55,112 --> 00:04:57,739
Right, but maybe smaller
thunderclaps for now

133
00:04:57,823 --> 00:04:59,282
and louder ones another time.

134
00:04:59,366 --> 00:05:01,159
Good night.

135
00:05:01,243 --> 00:05:03,787
Okay, guys, the first edition

136
00:05:03,871 --> 00:05:06,122
should include a mission statement.

137
00:05:06,206 --> 00:05:08,083
I agree.
There's no point in being subtle.

138
00:05:08,167 --> 00:05:09,960
It's the '60s, man.

139
00:05:10,044 --> 00:05:11,544
ABE, GUESTS: <i>♪ And the last fight ♪</i>

140
00:05:11,628 --> 00:05:13,338
<i>♪ Let us face ♪</i>

141
00:05:13,422 --> 00:05:14,547
ABE: Everybody!

142
00:05:14,631 --> 00:05:18,259
<i>♪ The Internationale ♪</i>

143
00:05:18,343 --> 00:05:19,593
-What?!
<i>-♪ Unites ♪</i>

144
00:05:19,677 --> 00:05:21,679
[ABE, GUESTS SPEAKING INDISTINCTLY]

145
00:05:32,857 --> 00:05:34,984
Your arrest was a gift from God, Abe,

146
00:05:35,068 --> 00:05:36,777
but now we got to exploit it.

147
00:05:36,861 --> 00:05:38,821
Publicize it, get you out there

148
00:05:38,905 --> 00:05:40,447
and make you the face of free speech.

149
00:05:40,531 --> 00:05:42,241
I want that. I want to be the face.

150
00:05:42,325 --> 00:05:43,951
You're the perfect image for the cause.

151
00:05:44,035 --> 00:05:46,787
Someone people can trust.
An éminence grise.

152
00:05:46,871 --> 00:05:48,454
I've always wanted to
be an éminence grise.

153
00:05:48,538 --> 00:05:50,498
I'm gonna get your work
notebooks back from Bell Labs.

154
00:05:50,582 --> 00:05:52,959
I'm peppering the shit out of
them with motions, hearings.

155
00:05:53,043 --> 00:05:54,961
In fact, I got something
you got to sign right now.

156
00:05:55,045 --> 00:05:56,879
They're my ideas, my thoughts.

157
00:05:56,963 --> 00:05:58,715
They belong to you.

158
00:05:58,799 --> 00:06:00,633
This is the last of the butter cookies.

159
00:06:00,717 --> 00:06:01,926
All right.

160
00:06:02,010 --> 00:06:03,886
Hey, you're communists,
for Christ's sake.

161
00:06:03,970 --> 00:06:04,887
Share.

162
00:06:04,971 --> 00:06:06,264
-Sorry.
-Of course.

163
00:06:06,348 --> 00:06:07,640
I can make eggs for
anyone who wants some.

164
00:06:07,724 --> 00:06:08,850
It's all right, Zelda.

165
00:06:08,934 --> 00:06:11,019
I'm sure having a maid
waiting on them like this,

166
00:06:11,103 --> 00:06:13,855
serving butter cookies,
is such a violation

167
00:06:13,939 --> 00:06:15,565
of their proletariat values.

168
00:06:15,649 --> 00:06:16,941
No, Abe, it's good, it's fine.

169
00:06:17,025 --> 00:06:18,692
Yeah, it helps us understand
what we're fighting against.

170
00:06:18,776 --> 00:06:21,903
You've yelled, you've argued,

171
00:06:21,987 --> 00:06:24,781
you've counterargued,
you've banged tables,

172
00:06:24,865 --> 00:06:27,576
you've banged walls, you've sung.

173
00:06:27,660 --> 00:06:28,577
"The Internationale."

174
00:06:28,661 --> 00:06:29,745
And a Chuck Berry song?

175
00:06:29,829 --> 00:06:31,330
We were taking a well-earned break.

176
00:06:31,414 --> 00:06:34,166
You've clapped hands,
you've clinked glasses.

177
00:06:34,250 --> 00:06:36,251
Someone was loud in the bathroom.

178
00:06:36,335 --> 00:06:38,086
-Sorry?
-ABE: You used the bathroom?

179
00:06:38,170 --> 00:06:39,755
-There was more singing.
-Which bathroom?

180
00:06:39,839 --> 00:06:42,215
-Miriam.
-Michael?

181
00:06:42,299 --> 00:06:43,967
You know Michael Kessler?
How do you know Michael Kessler?

182
00:06:44,051 --> 00:06:45,010
What are you doing here?

183
00:06:45,094 --> 00:06:46,553
-What are you doing here?
-I live here.

184
00:06:46,637 --> 00:06:48,012
How do you know Michael Kessler?

185
00:06:48,096 --> 00:06:49,930
-He's my lawyer.
-He's my lawyer.

186
00:06:50,014 --> 00:06:51,599
-What is he to you?
-My father.

187
00:06:51,683 --> 00:06:53,642
-Miriam's your daughter?
-Why do you have a lawyer?

188
00:06:53,726 --> 00:06:55,811
-He was arrested.
-Why were you arrested?

189
00:06:55,895 --> 00:06:57,730
-For protecting a man's rights.
-What man?

190
00:06:57,814 --> 00:06:59,106
-Lenny Bruce.
-Come again?

191
00:06:59,190 --> 00:07:00,733
-The man you're dating.
-You're dating Lenny Bruce?

192
00:07:00,817 --> 00:07:01,984
No, I am not dating Lenny Bruce.

193
00:07:02,068 --> 00:07:03,319
Excuse me, is Zelda part of this,

194
00:07:03,403 --> 00:07:04,528
or can she go make the eggs?

195
00:07:04,612 --> 00:07:06,781
Study.

196
00:07:06,865 --> 00:07:09,033
Move, move, move.

197
00:07:09,117 --> 00:07:11,202
Zelda. Eggs, now.

198
00:07:11,286 --> 00:07:12,578
Yes, miss.

199
00:07:12,662 --> 00:07:14,622
What is happening?

200
00:07:14,706 --> 00:07:17,333
You told me to go see
Lenny Bruce, so I did.

201
00:07:17,417 --> 00:07:19,209
This is too much for my brain.

202
00:07:19,293 --> 00:07:20,585
And more guys got in.

203
00:07:20,669 --> 00:07:23,046
-ABE: I'll speak to Ezra.
-And where is Mama?

204
00:07:23,130 --> 00:07:24,964
How is she sleeping
through the revolution?

205
00:07:25,048 --> 00:07:27,008
-She went home.
-This is home.

206
00:07:27,092 --> 00:07:29,386
-No, she went to see her family.
-She went to Providence?

207
00:07:29,470 --> 00:07:32,222
She wants to talk to them
about her share of the trust.

208
00:07:32,306 --> 00:07:34,224
Oh, boy, she hates Providence.

209
00:07:34,308 --> 00:07:36,351
But she needs a minimal lifestyle,

210
00:07:36,435 --> 00:07:37,769
and that takes money.

211
00:07:37,853 --> 00:07:38,937
You know me.

212
00:07:39,021 --> 00:07:41,439
I would sleep on the
cold street if need be,

213
00:07:41,523 --> 00:07:43,733
without bedding, forage for food.

214
00:07:43,817 --> 00:07:45,235
How do you want your eggs
this morning, Mr. Weissman?

215
00:07:45,319 --> 00:07:46,861
Uh, toad in the hole might be nice today.

216
00:07:46,945 --> 00:07:48,278
I see your shoes are off.

217
00:07:48,362 --> 00:07:50,697
-Are your corns bothering you again?
-A tad.

218
00:07:50,781 --> 00:07:52,116
We'll wash your feet, and I'll use

219
00:07:52,200 --> 00:07:53,700
-that pumice stone on them again.
-Perfect.

220
00:07:53,784 --> 00:07:56,203
But your mother,
she's not hearty like me.

221
00:07:56,287 --> 00:07:58,288
She needs her creature comforts.

222
00:07:58,372 --> 00:07:59,957
-And she's coming back?
-From Providence?

223
00:08:00,041 --> 00:08:01,250
Of course she's coming back.

224
00:08:01,334 --> 00:08:04,503
-And you're sure?
-Of course I'm sure.

225
00:08:04,587 --> 00:08:07,464
I'm pretty damn sure.

226
00:08:07,548 --> 00:08:11,343
Yes. From Providence, she will come back.

227
00:08:11,427 --> 00:08:16,890
<i>♪ The everlasting hills of Oklahoma ♪</i>

228
00:08:16,974 --> 00:08:19,475
<i>♪ They hold a million treasures ♪</i>

229
00:08:19,559 --> 00:08:23,146
<i>♪ To be found ♪</i>

230
00:08:23,230 --> 00:08:28,734
<i>♪ Golden grain on hills of green ♪</i>

231
00:08:28,818 --> 00:08:31,696
<i>♪ Wave to valleys ♪</i>

232
00:08:31,780 --> 00:08:34,449
<i>♪ Cool and clean ♪</i>

233
00:08:34,533 --> 00:08:37,243
<i>♪ Too bad some folks ♪</i>

234
00:08:37,327 --> 00:08:40,371
<i>♪ Have never seen ♪</i>

235
00:08:40,455 --> 00:08:42,707
<i>♪ The everlasting hills ♪</i>

236
00:08:42,791 --> 00:08:46,627
<i>♪ Of Oklahoma ♪</i>

237
00:08:46,711 --> 00:08:49,588
♪♪

238
00:08:52,716 --> 00:08:54,801
<i>♪ The everlasting tales ♪</i>

239
00:08:54,885 --> 00:08:58,054
<i>♪ Of Oklahoma ♪</i>

240
00:08:58,138 --> 00:08:59,556
<i>♪ Are told in clouded statues… ♪</i>

241
00:08:59,640 --> 00:09:01,766
Howdy, Rosie!

242
00:09:01,850 --> 00:09:04,352
-[BELL CLANGING]
-Rosie's home!

243
00:09:04,436 --> 00:09:07,147
<i>♪ Pioneers ♪</i>

244
00:09:07,231 --> 00:09:10,442
<i>-♪ Who long have gone ♪</i>
-[WHISTLE BLOWS]

245
00:09:10,526 --> 00:09:12,777
<i>♪ Their wagon wheels ♪</i>

246
00:09:12,861 --> 00:09:16,239
-Rosie's home.
<i>-♪ Still rumble on ♪</i>

247
00:09:16,323 --> 00:09:18,574
<i>♪ When thunder peals… ♪</i>

248
00:09:18,658 --> 00:09:20,826
Welcome home, my little Rosie.

249
00:09:20,910 --> 00:09:22,244
Hello, Helda, good to see you.

