734
00:26:33,032 --> 00:26:34,158
[WHISTLE BLOWS]

735
00:26:34,242 --> 00:26:37,453
I will let Oscar explain.

736
00:26:37,537 --> 00:26:40,706
[CLEARS THROAT] Our
little Rosie's here today

737
00:26:40,790 --> 00:26:42,750
because she'd like a little
more money from the trust.

738
00:26:42,834 --> 00:26:45,920
You see, Abe's been fired from his job,

739
00:26:46,004 --> 00:26:47,755
and additional funds are needed

740
00:26:47,839 --> 00:26:49,215
for Rose to maintain her quality of life.

741
00:26:49,299 --> 00:26:50,841
He wasn't fired.

742
00:26:50,925 --> 00:26:53,135
Just to be clear, he's
making a change in his life.

743
00:26:53,219 --> 00:26:56,513
Okay, I stand corrected.
He's making a change in his life.

744
00:26:56,597 --> 00:26:58,181
From employed to unemployed.

745
00:26:58,265 --> 00:26:59,390
[LAUGHTER]

746
00:26:59,474 --> 00:27:00,600
They move his classroom upstairs?

747
00:27:00,684 --> 00:27:01,851
Liev.

748
00:27:01,935 --> 00:27:05,355
Okay, okay, let's just
proceed on this now. Rosie?

749
00:27:05,439 --> 00:27:08,149
Thank you.
Just to elaborate, in my own words…

750
00:27:08,233 --> 00:27:09,901
Nope, I meant: could
you give us the room?

751
00:27:09,985 --> 00:27:11,486
-Why?
-We're about to vote.

752
00:27:11,570 --> 00:27:12,737
LIEV: Votes are done in secret.

753
00:27:12,821 --> 00:27:13,947
Rosie, you know that.

754
00:27:14,031 --> 00:27:15,949
Th… This is a family matter. I'm family.

755
00:27:16,033 --> 00:27:17,158
It's the rule.

756
00:27:17,242 --> 00:27:18,826
Well, how come he gets to stay?

757
00:27:18,910 --> 00:27:21,037
OSCAR: That's Mendel, that's Jacob's boy.

758
00:27:21,121 --> 00:27:22,163
-So?
-He's on the board.

759
00:27:22,247 --> 00:27:23,456
-Yeah!
-ROSE: He's a child.

760
00:27:23,540 --> 00:27:26,083
Yes, and someday he'll be a man.

761
00:27:26,167 --> 00:27:29,336
Plus, Uncle Mordecai retired
and we had an empty seat.

762
00:27:29,420 --> 00:27:32,214
You had two empty seats.
You never filled Grandmama's.

763
00:27:32,298 --> 00:27:34,049
Well, we were gonna
make Mendel Grandmama,

764
00:27:34,133 --> 00:27:36,426
but then Mordecai retired,
and so we made him Mordecai.

765
00:27:36,510 --> 00:27:37,678
And now we're out of men.

766
00:27:37,762 --> 00:27:39,388
-What about me?
-What about you?

767
00:27:39,472 --> 00:27:41,098
I could fill Grandmama's seat.

768
00:27:41,182 --> 00:27:43,559
-[LAUGHTER]
-What, that's funny?

769
00:27:43,643 --> 00:27:45,435
That I deserve to be
considered for the board?

770
00:27:45,519 --> 00:27:47,479
Board seats are filled
by the men of the family.

771
00:27:47,563 --> 00:27:49,231
-You know that.
-Grandmama was a girl.

772
00:27:49,315 --> 00:27:51,066
-Kinda.
-Grandmama started the business.

773
00:27:51,150 --> 00:27:52,734
They had to put her on the board.

774
00:27:52,818 --> 00:27:54,486
Well, how did Mendel earn his seat?

775
00:27:54,570 --> 00:27:55,987
-Oh, come on now, Rosie.
-Come on, what?

776
00:27:56,071 --> 00:27:57,989
Why have I never been
asked to be on the board?

777
00:27:58,073 --> 00:27:59,448
I'm a senior member of the family,

778
00:27:59,532 --> 00:28:01,742
there's an empty chair here
and some dumb little boy.

779
00:28:01,826 --> 00:28:04,036
She's mean. I vote no.

780
00:28:04,120 --> 00:28:06,122
That's not how you make
a decision, you little nitwit.

781
00:28:06,206 --> 00:28:08,666
-Stop.
-Rosie, don't get hysterical.

782
00:28:08,750 --> 00:28:09,288
I'm not hysterical.

783
00:28:09,372 --> 00:28:10,710
LIEV: You live in
New York, little sister.

784
00:28:10,794 --> 00:28:12,070
You don't know a thing
about the business.

785
00:28:12,154 --> 00:28:12,628
I could learn.

786
00:28:12,712 --> 00:28:14,380
I think your learning years
have long passed, Rosie.

787
00:28:14,464 --> 00:28:15,756
He doesn't know anything
about the business either.

788
00:28:15,840 --> 00:28:16,966
Excuse me?

789
00:28:17,050 --> 00:28:18,509
Come on, Oscar, you
walk around the fields

790
00:28:18,593 --> 00:28:19,719
asking workers if things are well.

791
00:28:19,803 --> 00:28:21,512
They say, "Yes." You say, "Very good."

792
00:28:21,596 --> 00:28:23,563
Then you come back inside.
I could do that.

793
00:28:23,647 --> 00:28:23,973
Rosie…

794
00:28:24,057 --> 00:28:26,433
"How are things, Bobby?"
"Well." "Yes." Done. Bye.

795
00:28:26,517 --> 00:28:28,351
Rosie, why don't you go
lay down and let us vote

796
00:28:28,435 --> 00:28:29,978
and give you your goddamn pin money.

797
00:28:30,062 --> 00:28:31,730
-Bad word!
-Shut up, Mendel.

798
00:28:31,814 --> 00:28:33,773
-Pin money?
-You want it or not?

799
00:28:33,857 --> 00:28:36,443
You know what I want.

800
00:28:36,527 --> 00:28:39,112
As a member of this family,
I want a seat on this board.

801
00:28:39,196 --> 00:28:40,488
It doesn't work that way.

802
00:28:40,572 --> 00:28:42,532
As a member of this
family who doesn't eat paste,

803
00:28:42,616 --> 00:28:45,285
-I demand a seat on this board.
-That's not gonna happen.

804
00:28:45,369 --> 00:28:48,872
Then clearly I'm not part of this family.

805
00:28:48,956 --> 00:28:50,540
And since I'm not a part of this family,

806
00:28:50,624 --> 00:28:52,125
I don't want anything
to do with this family.

807
00:28:52,209 --> 00:28:54,210
I don't care how much money
you throw at me, I'm done.

808
00:28:54,294 --> 00:28:56,128
-Rosie…
-It's very simple, if I don't get a say,

809
00:28:56,212 --> 00:28:57,338
I don't want your money!

810
00:28:57,422 --> 00:28:59,424
Any of it!

811
00:29:00,925 --> 00:29:03,177
Come on, Grandmama.

812
00:29:03,261 --> 00:29:05,972
Women aren't welcome here.

813
00:29:10,476 --> 00:29:12,478
[INDISTINCT CHATTER IN DISTANCE]

814
00:29:24,574 --> 00:29:26,867
What the fuck?

815
00:29:43,508 --> 00:29:45,135
[BAT THUDS]

816
00:29:59,899 --> 00:30:01,901
[OVERLAPPING CHATTER]

817
00:30:09,742 --> 00:30:11,243
Hey!

818
00:30:11,327 --> 00:30:13,203
[CHATTER STOPS]

819
00:30:13,287 --> 00:30:15,288
My name's Joel Maisel.

820
00:30:15,372 --> 00:30:17,999
I'm the sucker that
rented the space upstairs,

821
00:30:18,083 --> 00:30:20,252
and I'm not a cop.

822
00:30:20,336 --> 00:30:22,504
I'm just a guy.

823
00:30:22,588 --> 00:30:24,923
A guy in, uh, in need of information

824
00:30:25,007 --> 00:30:27,341
and, uh, a shower.

825
00:30:27,425 --> 00:30:29,009
Uh, I called the number on the lease,

826
00:30:29,093 --> 00:30:30,553
but it was disconnected.

827
00:30:30,637 --> 00:30:32,847
And there's only a post
office box and it's in Delaware,

828
00:30:32,931 --> 00:30:34,682
so I'm out of options.

829
00:30:34,766 --> 00:30:38,686
Now, I… I need to speak to the owner.

830
00:30:38,770 --> 00:30:41,313
And here's to hoping one
of you understands me.

831
00:30:41,397 --> 00:30:43,024
Thanks.

832
00:30:44,818 --> 00:30:46,444
Carry on.

833
00:30:55,620 --> 00:30:57,621
[CHATTER RESUMES]

834
00:31:03,085 --> 00:31:06,337
[OVERLAPPING CHATTER]

835
00:31:06,421 --> 00:31:07,964
-Hello there.
-Don't look at me.

836
00:31:08,048 --> 00:31:10,258
-I saved you a spot.
-You should have saved me two spots.

837
00:31:10,342 --> 00:31:12,677
-What are you talking about?
-This. This.

838
00:31:12,761 --> 00:31:14,721
I look like one of my
father's prize heifers.

839
00:31:14,805 --> 00:31:16,973
Imogene, you look just
like you did before the baby,

840
00:31:17,057 --> 00:31:18,641
tiny and perfect.

841
00:31:18,725 --> 00:31:20,393
CLAIRE: Ladies, take your place.

842
00:31:20,477 --> 00:31:24,230
-Doesn't she look great?
-Glad you're here, Imogene.

843
00:31:24,314 --> 00:31:27,733
Everyone, arms to the sky.

844
00:31:29,193 --> 00:31:30,319
Rag doll down.

845
00:31:30,403 --> 00:31:32,405
Shake it out.

846
00:31:34,073 --> 00:31:37,493
The divorcees are out in force, I see.

847
00:31:37,577 --> 00:31:39,912
-The new moms, too.
-Saved you a spot.

848
00:31:39,996 --> 00:31:42,247
Thanks, but no thanks, Isabelle.

849
00:31:42,331 --> 00:31:48,045
Now pick up your Hula-Hoops and… pulse.

850
00:31:48,129 --> 00:31:50,005
So what was the urgency
to come here today?

851
00:31:50,089 --> 00:31:51,673
Well, I heard how you let yourself go,

852
00:31:51,757 --> 00:31:53,342
and I had to see it for myself.

853
00:31:53,426 --> 00:31:55,636
-That's not funny.
-I have to get in shape for this tour.

854
00:31:55,720 --> 00:31:57,970
Oh, I want to hear more about the tour.

855
00:31:58,054 --> 00:32:00,306
-And to the right.
-It's 18 cities.

856
00:32:00,390 --> 00:32:01,558
And to the left.

857
00:32:02,976 --> 00:32:04,894
And again.

858
00:32:04,978 --> 00:32:07,021
18 cities? Wow.
You'll send me 18 postcards?

859
00:32:07,105 --> 00:32:09,190
-Of course.
-CLAIRE: Arms, ladies.

860
00:32:09,274 --> 00:32:10,608
Write down everything you experience.

861
00:32:10,692 --> 00:32:13,569
Everything you see and hear and eat.

862
00:32:13,653 --> 00:32:14,779
[GASPS] No, wait, not eat.

863
00:32:14,863 --> 00:32:16,030
CLAIRE: And change.

864
00:32:16,114 --> 00:32:17,949
You can't get fat from
reading about food, Imogene.

865
00:32:18,033 --> 00:32:18,991
You aren't a scientist.

866
00:32:19,075 --> 00:32:22,578
Now grab your isometric cords, ladies.

867
00:32:22,662 --> 00:32:25,540
I hope your weird little troll
of a manager's going with you.

868
00:32:25,624 --> 00:32:26,748
You need a guard dog.

869
00:32:26,832 --> 00:32:28,625
Things happen on the road, dirty things,

870
00:32:28,709 --> 00:32:30,669
-and write them all down, please.
-Mount your boards.

871
00:32:30,753 --> 00:32:32,212
-Yes, Susie's going.
-Why the tone?

872
00:32:32,296 --> 00:32:33,505
CLAIRE: And twist.

873
00:32:35,633 --> 00:32:36,925
We're on the outs right now.

874
00:32:37,009 --> 00:32:39,219
She took on a new client, Sophie Lennon.

875
00:32:39,303 --> 00:32:41,346
Wow, Sophie Lennon, that's big.

876
00:32:41,430 --> 00:32:42,597
I hate Sophie Lennon.

877
00:32:42,681 --> 00:32:44,057
Oh, right, we hate Sophie Lennon.

878
00:32:44,141 --> 00:32:45,267
I forget that.

879
00:32:45,351 --> 00:32:46,560
CLAIRE: Figure eights down.

880
00:32:46,644 --> 00:32:48,019
It was just too much too soon,

881
00:32:48,103 --> 00:32:50,188
her taking on Sophie.

882
00:32:50,272 --> 00:32:52,357
I need her full-time.
It's like she abandoned me.

883
00:32:52,441 --> 00:32:54,401
Abandoned you?
She dropped you? What a jerk.

884
00:32:54,485 --> 00:32:56,819
No, she's still my manager,
but I shouldn't have to share her.

885
00:32:56,903 --> 00:32:58,571
So you're saying she
makes enough off of just you

886
00:32:58,655 --> 00:33:00,155
that she doesn't need
to have any other clients?

887
00:33:00,239 --> 00:33:01,866
Well, not quite.

888
00:33:01,950 --> 00:33:04,785
I think she only made about
20 bucks off me last year.

889
00:33:04,869 --> 00:33:06,871
-Swing arms.
-So you're saying

890
00:33:06,955 --> 00:33:09,331
she has enough of a savings
to have you as her only client?

891
00:33:09,415 --> 00:33:10,875
Well, not quite.

892
00:33:10,959 --> 00:33:12,501
I don't think she has any savings.

893
00:33:12,585 --> 00:33:14,169
She probably doesn't
even have a bank account.

894
00:33:14,253 --> 00:33:16,422
But going out on tour
opening for Shy Baldwin,

895
00:33:16,506 --> 00:33:18,299
the money's gonna come pouring in, right?

896
00:33:18,383 --> 00:33:21,969
Well, not quite.
It's not even a living for me.

897
00:33:22,053 --> 00:33:24,763
-But Susie gets half, right?
-CLAIRE: And saw.

898
00:33:24,847 --> 00:33:27,223
-Well, not quite.
-IMOGENE: Oh.

899
00:33:27,307 --> 00:33:28,892
But, no, I agree.

900
00:33:28,976 --> 00:33:33,104
You're Miriam Maisel,
<i>you</i> should be enough.

901
00:33:33,188 --> 00:33:36,900
Yeah. I should be enough.

902
00:33:36,984 --> 00:33:38,902
Can you move? I can't see.

903
00:33:38,986 --> 00:33:41,237
I had a baby four weeks ago!

904
00:33:41,321 --> 00:33:43,406
And your husband drinks.

905
00:33:43,490 --> 00:33:44,490
Feel better?

906
00:33:44,574 --> 00:33:46,910
Little bit. Yeah.

907
00:33:53,583 --> 00:33:56,377
ABE: Rose? Rose!

908
00:33:56,461 --> 00:33:58,503
Wonderful, you're back.

909
00:33:58,587 --> 00:34:01,173
I mean, I knew you were coming
back, I looked in your closet,

910
00:34:01,257 --> 00:34:02,883
but sometimes you don't come back.

911
00:34:02,967 --> 00:34:05,677
So it's nice that you came back.

912
00:34:05,761 --> 00:34:07,512
It is you, isn't it?

913
00:34:07,596 --> 00:34:09,765
You don't look like yourself.

914
00:34:09,849 --> 00:34:11,558
Can I get you something?
Something to drink?

915
00:34:11,642 --> 00:34:13,644
Something to eat?

916
00:34:14,645 --> 00:34:16,480
Rose?

917
00:34:16,564 --> 00:34:19,816
I have just come from a travel
odyssey of biblical proportions.

918
00:34:19,900 --> 00:34:21,318
Oh, dear.

919
00:34:21,402 --> 00:34:23,153
Hieronymus Bosch couldn't
have conjured the world

920
00:34:23,237 --> 00:34:25,781
I've inhabited for the past 25 hours.

921
00:34:25,865 --> 00:34:29,742
-Oh, you had a bad flight.
-I suppose you could say that.

922
00:34:29,826 --> 00:34:32,203
My first plane sat on
the tarmac for five hours.

923
00:34:32,287 --> 00:34:33,955
-Oh.
-The second plane hit turbulence

924
00:34:34,039 --> 00:34:35,706
that felt like the very hands of God

925
00:34:35,790 --> 00:34:38,125
were tearing the plane into shreds.

926
00:34:38,209 --> 00:34:41,587
A suitcase fell on my head and
a child threw up on my handbag.

927
00:34:41,671 --> 00:34:44,715
-Oh, your poor handbag.
-We had to land at San Diego,

928
00:34:44,799 --> 00:34:47,093
which is in the opposite
direction of New York City.

929
00:34:47,177 --> 00:34:50,137
So, 12 hours in, I'm
1,300 miles farther away

930
00:34:50,221 --> 00:34:52,848
from where I'm trying
to go, and who is that?

931
00:34:52,932 --> 00:34:54,100
ABE: Oh, that's Ezra.

932
00:34:54,184 --> 00:34:56,060
He had an argument with his old lady.

933
00:34:56,144 --> 00:34:58,311
Just needed a place to
crash for a couple of days.

934
00:34:58,395 --> 00:34:59,437
MIDGE: Is that Mama?

935
00:34:59,521 --> 00:35:00,897
-Is she home?
-Kind of.

936
00:35:00,981 --> 00:35:02,482
From San Diego, all that was available

937
00:35:02,566 --> 00:35:03,942
was a plane to Philadelphia,

938
00:35:04,026 --> 00:35:06,903
so I took that and thought I'd
train from there to New York,

939
00:35:06,987 --> 00:35:08,446
but the boiler men are on strike,

940
00:35:08,530 --> 00:35:09,781
which forced me to take a bus,

941
00:35:09,865 --> 00:35:11,866
where I was groped by
a little man in a fedora.

942
00:35:11,950 --> 00:35:13,159
And, I'm sorry, who is that?

943
00:35:13,243 --> 00:35:16,162
Uh, that's Mr. Curtis.
He's from Columbia.

944
00:35:16,246 --> 00:35:18,373
Yes, ma'am.
I'm just getting some measurements

945
00:35:18,457 --> 00:35:20,625
for the next occupant, a Nobel Laureate.

946
00:35:20,709 --> 00:35:22,502
Exciting stuff for us.

947
00:35:22,586 --> 00:35:24,713
Oh, I'm glad you're
excited, Mr. Curtis, very glad.

948
00:35:24,797 --> 00:35:25,964
Say, are you planning on taking

949
00:35:26,048 --> 00:35:27,382
these drapes with you? They're nice.

950
00:35:27,466 --> 00:35:29,800
Yes, we're taking the
drapes with us, Mr. Curtis.

951
00:35:29,884 --> 00:35:32,511
We're taking anything
and everything of value

952
00:35:32,595 --> 00:35:33,971
which we could possibly hock,

953
00:35:34,055 --> 00:35:35,848
or in the case of drapes,
make into clothing.

954
00:35:35,932 --> 00:35:37,099
I don't understand.

955
00:35:37,183 --> 00:35:38,767
I'm gonna have to get
some Butterick patterns.

956
00:35:38,851 --> 00:35:40,936
May I use that to measure
my husband for pants?

957
00:35:41,020 --> 00:35:43,313
Did the family not extend you more money?

958
00:35:43,397 --> 00:35:45,607
Whoa. Mama, what happened to you?

959
00:35:45,691 --> 00:35:47,693
What happened to me?

960
00:35:47,777 --> 00:35:51,572
My condescending, sniggering
family was so goddamn awful,

961
00:35:51,656 --> 00:35:53,198
I gave up my trust fund entirely.

962
00:35:53,282 --> 00:35:54,658
That's what happened to me.

963
00:35:54,742 --> 00:35:56,702
-I'm sorry, what?
-I gave up the money. I don't want it.

964
00:35:56,786 --> 00:35:57,994
It's blood money.

965
00:35:58,078 --> 00:35:59,746
-But…
-But what?

966
00:35:59,830 --> 00:36:02,290
Well, Rose, we need that money.

967
00:36:02,374 --> 00:36:03,708
We can't live without that money.

968
00:36:03,792 --> 00:36:04,917
What's a little blood?

969
00:36:05,001 --> 00:36:07,503
That money was a yoke. Now I am unyoked.

970
00:36:07,587 --> 00:36:08,755
Untethered. Free.

971
00:36:08,839 --> 00:36:09,922
I don't believe this.

972
00:36:10,006 --> 00:36:11,340
What?

973
00:36:11,424 --> 00:36:12,967
Miriam, what… what don't you believe?

974
00:36:13,051 --> 00:36:15,094
You. Th… The both of you.

975
00:36:15,178 --> 00:36:17,221
You quit Columbia,
you lose the apartment.

976
00:36:17,305 --> 00:36:19,057
You go to beef up your trust fund,

977
00:36:19,141 --> 00:36:20,600
you come back without a trust fund.

978
00:36:20,684 --> 00:36:23,269
I mean, what is going on with you two?

